<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
POSPICH CLAIMS OJAI TENNIS SINGLES TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Natasha Pospich of Woodland Hills won the girls' 18-and-under singles title and 
Camarillo's sister duo of Amelia and Molly White won the girls' 16-and-under 
doubles championship Saturday at the 91st Ojai Valley Tennis tournament. 
</P>
<P>
In men's junior college doubles, Pierce's Al Martinez and Jason Gary advanced 
to today's final with a 6-4, 6-2 win over Grossmont's Kelly and Mike Asvig. 
</P>
<P>
Cypress' John Swaino defeated Martinez, 6-2, 6-4, in the semifinals of the 
men's junior college singles. Golden West's Andy Stewart defeated Gary, 6-1, 
6-1, in the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
Pospich beat Ditta Huber of La Jolla, 6-1, 6-4, in the final. 
</P>
<P>
Amelia and Molly White bested Amanda and Amber Basica of Lomita, 2-6, 6-4, 6-1, 
to win the doubles title. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL BASEBALL 
</P>
<P>
Crespi 3, Torrance 0 -- Freshman right-hander Jeff Suppan (3-2) threw a 
no-hitter in a consolation game of the Redondo-Palos Verdes tournament at 
Pierce College. 
</P>
<P>
Crespi (14-7-1), which recorded a one-hitter in a 1-0 defeat of previously 
unbeaten St. John Bosco on Friday, has a streak of 18 consecutive scoreless 
innings. 
</P>
<P>
Culver City 3, Alemany 2 (11 innings) -- Freshmen pitchers Rob Nary and Eddie 
Bushey combined on an eight-hitter, but Culver City's Mauricio Estavil hit a 
solo homer with nobody out in the bottom of the 11th in a Redondo-Palos Verdes 
tournament game. 
</P>
<P>
Steve Pacheco and Leo Tejada each had two hits for Alemany (12-11). 
</P>
<P>
Palos Verdes 5, Notre Dame 4 -- Vinnie Orlando hit a two-run homer in the first 
inning, but Notre Dame (13-10-1) didn't manage another hit until Kevin 
Milligan's single in the sixth in a consolation game of the Redondo-Palos 
Verdes tournament. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
COLLEGE BASEBALL 
</P>
<P>
Ventura 5, Pierce 3 -- Right-hander Mike Teron earned a win and drove in three 
runs with three hits to lead host Ventura (21-14, 10-10) in a Western State 
Conference game. 
</P>
<P>
Carl McFadden had three hits and Scott Cadenhead added two for Pierce (16-21, 
7-13). 
</P>
<P>
Cal Lutheran 9-5, Pomona-Pitzer 3-2 -- Dave Leonhardt was six for eight and 
Peter Washington and Leonard Matsumoto each hit solo home runs for Cal Lutheran 
(25-11) in a nonconference doubleheader. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
SOFTBALL 
</P>
<P>
Cal Lutheran 4-4, UC San Diego 3-1 -- Leslie Stevens' one-out single drove in 
the game-winning run in the 11th inning in the opener, and Stevens tossed a 
six-hitter in the nightcap for Cal Lutheran (29-10). Cal Lutheran extended its 
winning streak to five games. 
</P>
<P>
Hart 6, Agoura 0 -- Hart pitcher Kym Weil struck out 21 batters and surrendered 
just six singles in two games of the Thousand Oaks tournament. 
</P>
<P>
Weil pitched a one-hitter, walked none and fanned nine Santa Paula batters in a 
6-0 first-round win. In a championship quarterfinal against defending Southern 
Section 1-A Division champion Agoura (14-5), Hawaii-bound Weil (19-1) recorded 
12 strikeouts and allowed five singles in a 6-0 win. 
</P>
<P>
The Indians (20-2) will face Newbury Park in a championship semifinal Saturday 
at Los Cerritos Park. 
</P>
<P>
Agoura 1, Notre Dame 0 -- Melissa Thatcher (14-4) threw a three-hitter and was 
two for three to lead Agoura (14-4) in a Thousand Oaks tournament game. 
</P>
<P>
Thatcher (14-4) struck out four and walked four and teammate Rachel Clarke 
drove in the game's lone run with a two-out single in the third. 
</P>
<P>
Notre Dame 1, Santa Paula 0 -- Senior right-hander Becca Berline pitched a 
no-hitter and came within a fifth-inning of a perfect game in a consolation 
game of the Thousand Oaks tournament. 
</P>
<P>
Berline (12-6) faced 21 batters, struck out nine and walked none. Notre Dame is 
12-6. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
COLLEGE SWIMMING 
</P>
<P>
Western State Conference Championships -- Valley College finished third in both 
the men's and women's divisions at Valley College. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Monica won the men's team title with 437 points, followed by Ventura with 
417 and Valley with 341. Canyons was fifth with 246 and Pierce was last with 
143. 
</P>
<P>
Ventura won the women's team title with 421 points, followed by Cuesta with 386 
and Valley with 351. Canyons was fifth with 139 and Pierce last with 90. 
</P>
