<P>
Photo, Design Class Project Is All Fluff: Industrial design students at 
Pasadena's Art Center College of Design geared up for a battle of the 
marshmallows recently as part of a visual communications class assignment. 
Students spent 14 weeks designing marshmallow-launching contraptions. The 
school's atrium was divided into 21 "planets," and the students were paired up 
in teams of two, with each team inhabiting one of the "planets." Each team was 
equipped with about 60 "space probes" (marshmallows) and had two hours to 
launch the probes from their planet to the other 20. At top, Tony Cruz loads 
his XP Super Space Modulator with a marshmallow while space partner Steve 
Caterson prepares to launch it. Meanwhile, Joe Ponce and Jim Elliott, center, 
ready their Bellows-Activated Marshmallow Launcher for action, and long-haired 
John Schrenk and Steve Eum, bottom, blast marshmallows from their Mad Max Twin 
Cam Industrial Shooter. While Deana Schoenegge checks the barrel of her 
launcher, white-faced Michael Lindars and Cheryl Johnson take a respite from 
the battle to share a laugh. IRFAN KHAN / For The Times 
</P>
