<HEADLINE>
<P>
RERUNS TO RE-WATCH: THE JOKER'S WILD ON 'BATMAN' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOAN FANTAZIA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Joker plans to laugh all the way to the bank -- well, actually the Federal 
Depository -- on "Batman" (Sunday at 2 p.m. on KTTV). 
</P>
<P>
Blowing open the depository and cleaning the place out is a big job. 
</P>
<P>
It'll take two villains-the Joker (Cesar Romero) and Catwoman (Eartha Kitt)-to 
pull it off in "The Funny Feline Felonies." The pair return in the second part, 
called "The Joke's on the Catwoman" (2:30 p.m.) 
</P>
<P>
Catwoman didn't get involved just because the Joker needed a hand; at the time, 
the show itself did too. During the series' third and final season, villains 
were teamed in episodes to try to boost the sagging ratings of the once-wildly 
popular show. 
</P>
<P>
But no matter how many villains are on the same team, they can't keep a good 
Batman down. The Caped Crusader (Adam West) and his colleagues, Robin (Burt 
Ward) and Batgirl (Yvonne Craig), triumph as always with their wits, moral 
strength-and enough gadgets to put Ronco out of business. 
</P>
<P>
Watch for a mistake in the episode: The Joker is surprised to learn that the 
heroes are alive, but the scene that shows how he tried to kill them was cut 
out. 
</P>
<P>
Later in the week, there is no pairing of guest villains in "The Impractical 
Joker/The Joker's Provokers" (Saturday at 2 p.m. on KTTV), which is from the 
second season. The Joker does his dirty work with only a couple of thugs and 
his girlfriend, Cornelia (played by Kathy Kersh, who at the time was Ward's 
wife). 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, Before there was Jack Nicholson, the Joker was played in all his 
resplendency by Cesar Romero on the TV version of "Batman." 
